	<div id="id1912" class="post">
		<h2 class="title"><span class="image-wrapper"><img height="45" alt="Stinkin’ BBQ" width="218" class="title" src="../../../resources/net.databinder.components.RenderedLabel/aa20b6a9"/><span class="title">Stinkin’ BBQ</span></span></h2>
		<div class="byline"><span>
			<span>By <span class="alias">Doctor Barnett</span>, <span>on March 27, 2006</span></span>
			<span id="id1913" class="tags">
					{&nbsp;<span><a href="../../../city/tag/food/#selected-tag"><span>food</span></a></span>&nbsp;}
			</span>
		</span></div>
		<div><p style="float:right"><img src="/pictures/bbq.jpg" alt="" />
<div style="float:right"><img src="/pictures/bbq-vent.jpg" alt="" /></div>
<div style="float:right"><img src="/pictures/bbq-neon.jpg" alt="" /></div></p>


	<p>I’ll be as specific as possible here: “BBQ Restaurant,” at 21 University Place, stinks to high heaven. (Yes, it’s just <span class="caps">BBQ</span>. Spare name, gluttonous business.)</p>


	<p>Every morning and evening I attempt to follow a route that keeps me the required one-block distance away from stench-ground-zero. But when the crosswalk signals don’t work out and I’m forced to walk in front of that monstrosity, it is infallibly disgusting. Airborne grease. I’ve never smelled anything like it.</p>


	<p>Except one place. Walking in line to recess at my (later tornado-ravaged) elementary school, we had to pass by the back side of the cafeteria. Ew. It was a while before we realized that the smell had anything to do with “food.” It was nasty.</p>


	<p>I never thought that, twenty years later, I would find exactly the same revolting smell camping out in some of the most expensive real estate in the country.</p>


	<p>That’s something I don’t understand about Manhattanites. Why, oh why, do you put up with such shit? You pay an incredible amount of money to live where you do, and then you allow conditions to prevail that wouldn’t pass muster in a modern day country elementary school.</p>


	<p>Three quarters of us have no car, yet we permit them to run us down. We allow them to blow their horns at will, at any hour. Garbage trucks after midnight seem to always travel in reverse. Street vendors take up most of the sidewalk. It’s noisy and disgusting here, and no one cares.</p>


	<p>It’s that culture of apathy that bothers me more than these problems themselves. It’s as if all New Yorkers have decided, on the advice of their therapists, to just let everything go because there’s nothing you can do about it.</p>


	<p>Which is bullshit. Even if I didn’t believe in majority power, I would believe in monetary power. There’s enough money affected by the stench of “BBQ Restaurant” to finance the next lunar mission, and take that greasy kitchen with it.</p>


	<p>Until that happens, I suppose I’ll keep ostentatiously holding my nose as I walk by, contemplating the misfirings of a free market and-<del>against my will</del>-the horrors of my school cafeteria.</p></div>
